 "segments": [
  {
   "start": 0.0,
   "end": 3.28,
   "text": "Try to order two beers in Chinese, and you've just made a grammar mistake."
  },
  {
   "start": 3.9,
   "end": 5.32,
   "text": "You literally cannot say two beer."
  },
  {
   "start": 5.72,
   "end": 9.18,
   "text": "You need a special little word in between, and Chinese has more than a hundred of them."
  },
  {
   "start": 9.52,
   "end": 10.12,
   "text": "Here's the rule."
  },
  {
   "start": 10.58,
   "end": 13.18,
   "text": "In Chinese, you can't stick a number straight onto a noun."
  },
  {
   "start": 13.72,
   "end": 16.22,
   "text": "No two beer, no three dog, no five book."
  },
  {
   "start": 16.68,
   "end": 20.06,
   "text": "Between the number and the thing, you need a measure word, a classifier."
  },
  {
   "start": 20.68,
   "end": 25.18,
   "text": "So two beers becomes literally two bottles beer, Lang Ping Pijo."
  },
  {
   "start": 25.76,
   "end": 28.2,
   "text": "That little ping bottle is the measure word."
  },
  {
   "start": 28.2,
   "end": 31.46,
   "text": "Leave it out, and it's broken Chinese, and it goes deeper."
  },
  {
   "start": 31.78,
   "end": 33.78,
   "text": "Even the word two is special here."
  },
  {
   "start": 34.36,
   "end": 39.7,
   "text": "Normally, two is r, but right before a measure word, it changes to a different word, liang."
  },
  {
   "start": 40.22,
   "end": 43.78,
   "text": "So even counting to two trips people up, and then there's the real mountain."
  },
  {
   "start": 44.04,
   "end": 46.34,
   "text": "There are over 150 of these measure words."
  },
  {
   "start": 46.8,
   "end": 50.06,
   "text": "And which one you use depends on the shape or type of thing."
  },
  {
   "start": 50.56,
   "end": 55.52,
   "text": "Flat things, long things, animals, books, machines, many have their own."
  },
  {
   "start": 55.88,
   "end": 56.7,
   "text": "But here's the relief."
  },
  {
   "start": 56.7,
   "end": 60.96,
   "text": "One general measure word, G-E, and that works for the huge majority of cases."
  },
  {
   "start": 61.46,
   "end": 63.8,
   "text": "By some counts, around 94% of the time."
  },
  {
   "start": 63.96,
   "end": 66.82,
   "text": "So if you blank on the exact one, G will usually save you."
  },
  {
   "start": 67.36,
   "end": 68.96,
   "text": "Not always perfect, but understood."
  },
  {
   "start": 69.62,
   "end": 71.98,
   "text": "In English, two just works on everything."
  },
  {
   "start": 72.62,
   "end": 76.36,
   "text": "In Chinese, you have to know what kind of thing you're counting before you can count it."
  },
  {
   "start": 76.82,
   "end": 79.78,
   "text": "Which is why ordering two beers is secretly a grammar exam."
  },
  {
   "start": 80.24,
   "end": 81.54,
   "text": "Want to actually start learning Chinese?"
  },
  {
   "start": 81.54,
   "end": 86.0,
   "text": "Discover thousands of free exercises and more learning content on stacktags.io."
  }
